{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0dca44e2-3c9f-4b10-bf2c-165fea45bd9a","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but I can answer from general .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — the OS writes a Mach-O core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that:\n   - The binary isn't codesigned with the `com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory` restriction.\n   - SIP isn't blocking core dumps. On Apple Silicon you may need to boot into Recovery and run `csrutil enable --without dtrace`.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n6. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS/dotnet diagnostics plugin in lldb:\n   ```bash\n   (lldb) plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   (lldb) clrstack\n   ```\n   Note: SOS support for NativeAOT dumps is limited — native backtraces with symbols are often more useful.\n\n**Key point:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`, so you rely on the OS-level core dump facility (`/cores/`). Ensure `ulimit -c unlimited` is set *before* launching the app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2feb8f9b-7f9f-4907-a6fc-f31c81d14e1c","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"942A:A7934:253E2B:2C811A:69E82021"},"id":"959adfbf-5c17-423f-ab1c-0df9263a49e9","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:11:08.525Z","parentId":"98bf1d80-b3fe-4f4f-a339-c83fef6c0067"}
